    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-04-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-04-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                <head>138. Memorandum of Conference With President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d138fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Papers, DDE Diaries. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_Walters1">Walters</persName> on April 27. The conference
                        took place in the Red Room at the White House when <persName
                            corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName> called to say goodbye.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1960-04-26">April 26, 1960</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>OTHERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">de Gaulle</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_Walters1">Colonel Walters</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The President asked General <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName>
                    whether he had read <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>’s speech
                    at Baku<note n="1" xml:id="d138fn1">For extracts of <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                            >Khrushchev</persName>’s April 25 speech at Baku, in which he reiterated
                        the maximum Soviet demands on Germany and Berlin, see <hi rend="italic"
                            >American Foreign Policy: Current Documents</hi>, 1960, pp.
                        404–406.</note> and General <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName>
                    said he had. The President said that one thing that bothered him about these
                    speeches of <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>’s is that having
                    taken these extremely firm positions he found himself obliged to abide by them.
                    General <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">de Gaulle</persName> said that he did say
                    these things, but he was not sure he really meant them, and he did feel that
                    sometime during the conference we would probably have to say “No” to Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>, and the President nodded
                    agreement.</p>
                <p>On taking leave of the President, General <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">de
                        Gaulle</persName> said “Now that I have seen you I have even greater
                    confidence in our cause.” The President replied, “We shall be standing
                    together.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_Walters1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Vernon Walters</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d138fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Colonel U.S. Army</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
